<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What was William Jennings Bryan criticizing in his "Cross of Gold" speech?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">The use of paper money</option>
            <option letter="b">Religious symbolism in currency</option>
            <option letter="c">The exclusive gold standard</option>
            <option letter="d">International trade policies</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>Bryan's famous speech criticized the gold standard as harmful to farmers and workers, advocating instead for bimetallism (using both silver and gold).</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>When a bank has excess reserves, it typically:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Returns them to the Fed</option>
            <option letter="b">Makes loans or buys securities</option>
            <option letter="c">Distributes them to shareholders</option>
            <option letter="d">Converts them to currency</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Banks typically use excess reserves to make loans or buy securities, as these activities earn interest income rather than letting reserves sit idle.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Why did the Bretton Woods system ultimately fail?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">The IMF ran out of funding</option>
            <option letter="b">The US couldn't maintain gold convertibility</option>
            <option letter="c">World War III broke out</option>
            <option letter="d">All countries adopted the euro</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The system failed because the US couldn't maintain the dollar's convertibility to gold at $35/oz due to increasing trade deficits and foreign dollar holdings.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What is the primary difference between commodity money and fiat money?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Only governments can issue fiat money</option>
            <option letter="b">Commodity money has intrinsic value</option>
            <option letter="c">Fiat money cannot be counterfeited</option>
            <option letter="d">Commodity money is always metallic</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The key difference is that commodity money has intrinsic value (like gold or silver), while fiat money's value comes from government decree and public trust.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does the Fed's discount window serve as "lender of last resort"?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It lends only to foreign banks</option>
            <option letter="b">It provides emergency loans to troubled banks</option>
            <option letter="c">It only lends to the Treasury</option>
            <option letter="d">It guarantees all bank deposits</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>As lender of last resort, the Fed's discount window provides emergency loans to solvent but illiquid banks when other funding sources are unavailable.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
